WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:05.800
These two gentlemen, Diffie and Helmann, actually came up with an idea, and they published

00:05.800 --> 00:10.040
a paper called New Directions in Cryptography.

00:30.000 --> 00:51.480
In this module, we're going to describe asymmetric key cryptography and how it works, so if you

00:51.480 --> 00:59.520
remember to what the advantages and disadvantages of symmetric cryptography are, it's very fast,

00:59.520 --> 01:02.680
but it has this problem of key distribution.

01:02.680 --> 01:08.720
People have been thinking about this problem of key distribution for thousands of years.

01:08.720 --> 01:15.360
And in 1976, these two gentlemen, Diffie and Helmann, actually came up with an idea,

01:15.360 --> 01:21.200
and they published a paper called New Directions in Cryptography, because they talked about

01:21.200 --> 01:28.720
how there might be a different way to do cryptography that gets rid of the problem of key distribution.

01:28.720 --> 01:34.040
And so they published a paper called New Directions in Cryptography, and within it, they actually

01:34.040 --> 01:38.440
described this process, and they actually called it public key cryptography, and that's

01:38.440 --> 01:41.040
why a lot of people still call it that today.

01:41.040 --> 01:46.280
But it should really be called asymmetric key cryptography, and what they went on to describe

01:46.280 --> 01:53.320
basically is that they said, okay, if you think about symmetric, you know, we need the

01:53.320 --> 02:00.520
same key at both ends, and that requires key distribution, which in many cases is a very

02:00.520 --> 02:02.040
big problem.

02:02.040 --> 02:08.040
So they went on to describe how, what if everybody has two keys instead of one?

02:08.040 --> 02:10.360
So I would have my own two keys.

02:10.360 --> 02:12.080
You would have your own two keys.

02:12.080 --> 02:15.200
This person over here has their own two keys.

02:15.200 --> 02:17.120
Everybody has a key pair.

02:17.120 --> 02:22.680
But most importantly, the two keys, for example that I have, are related to each other

02:22.680 --> 02:23.680
mathematically.

02:23.680 --> 02:29.280
There's a mathematical relationship that links my two keys together.

02:29.280 --> 02:35.960
The idea is, if I use one to encrypt, you can never use the same one to decrypt.

02:35.960 --> 02:36.960
It's not possible.

02:36.960 --> 02:39.080
You have to use the other one.

02:39.080 --> 02:43.120
And the reason this works is because the two are linked mathematically.

02:43.120 --> 02:47.240
So if I use this one to encrypt, it's this one that decrypts.

02:47.240 --> 02:50.840
If I use this one to encrypt, it's this other one that decrypts.

02:50.840 --> 02:53.920
You can never encrypt and decrypt with the same key.

02:53.920 --> 03:00.840
So the idea is, I'm going to take one of my keys and I'm going to give it to anyone, the

03:00.840 --> 03:05.480
whole world possibly, that may want to communicate with me securely.

03:05.480 --> 03:10.760
And because I'm going to give that key to anyone who may want to communicate with me securely,

03:10.760 --> 03:13.240
I'm going to call that one my public key.

03:13.240 --> 03:16.440
So the entire world may have my public key.

03:16.440 --> 03:22.400
But if anyone wants to communicate with me securely, a secret message, let's say, they

03:22.400 --> 03:26.480
will encrypt that message with my public key.

03:26.480 --> 03:33.040
And even though everyone else has my public key, nobody can read that message because you

03:33.040 --> 03:37.400
can never encrypt and decrypt with the same key, it has to be the other one.

03:37.400 --> 03:44.280
So if anyone out there encrypts a message with my public key, the only key that can decrypt

03:44.280 --> 03:47.800
is the other key that I keep private to myself.

03:47.800 --> 03:54.720
This key, I will never disclose, communicate, divulge or send to anyone else.

03:54.720 --> 03:57.600
I will always keep it private to myself.

03:57.600 --> 04:00.640
That's why I'm going to call that my private key.

04:00.640 --> 04:05.160
So this solves the problem of key distribution, doesn't it?

04:05.160 --> 04:10.520
Because the only key that I ever have to distribute is my public key and I don't care how many

04:10.520 --> 04:11.520
people have it.

04:11.520 --> 04:16.000
In fact, I can assume that the entire world has my public key.

04:16.000 --> 04:23.000
As long as I keep my other private key that is associated with it, private to myself,

04:23.000 --> 04:28.200
it's very important to keep the private key private to myself, never disclose it, communicate

04:28.200 --> 04:29.520
it, and so on.

04:29.520 --> 04:36.520
This solves the problem of key distribution, but it actually introduces another problem

04:36.520 --> 04:38.840
that is pretty substantial.

04:38.840 --> 04:44.360
And that is the only way that this works is because the two keys are related to each

04:44.360 --> 04:46.200
other mathematically.

04:46.200 --> 04:51.640
So if I give my public key out to the entire world, I've got to make sure that nobody

04:51.640 --> 04:59.080
out there can use my public key and compute the mathematical relationship that links my

04:59.080 --> 05:00.880
two keys together.

05:00.880 --> 05:05.480
Because if that was possible, anybody out there that has my public key will be able to

05:05.480 --> 05:11.720
compute the relationship and therefore derive knowledge of my private key by having access

05:11.720 --> 05:13.720
to my public key.

05:13.720 --> 05:16.280
And so we have to be able to prevent that.

05:16.280 --> 05:22.240
And the only way that we can prevent this is to use or to link the two keys together

05:22.240 --> 05:30.240
using really hard math and use really large numbers in that hard math.

05:30.240 --> 05:36.760
The idea is whoever has my public key may be able to compute what the relationship is.

05:36.760 --> 05:42.800
But because we are using hard math and very large numbers, given today's technology in

05:42.800 --> 05:48.040
our speed of processors, it would take that person hundreds of years in order to be able

05:48.040 --> 05:55.240
to compute as long as we're using really large numbers to link the two keys together.

05:55.240 --> 05:56.880
And so it's possible.

05:56.880 --> 06:02.120
But because we're using really large numbers, it's not feasible and no one's even going

06:02.120 --> 06:07.080
to try because it's going to take too much computational power to derive knowledge.

06:07.080 --> 06:14.080
And one of the issues that we have with asymmetric key cryptography is as processors become faster

06:14.080 --> 06:17.360
and technology improves, guess what we have to do?

06:17.360 --> 06:23.760
We have to keep increasing the size of those numbers that link the two keys together.

06:23.760 --> 06:29.240
The problem is this because we have to use hard math and really large numbers.

06:29.240 --> 06:35.800
This becomes computationally intensive and therefore there's a price to pay.

06:35.800 --> 06:42.320
The price to pay is that this type of cryptography becomes really slow as a result because of

06:42.320 --> 06:47.960
that mathematical intensity that links the two keys together.

06:47.960 --> 06:53.400
So because we're using really large numbers, it's going to take a really long time to encrypt

06:53.400 --> 06:55.000
and decrypt with the two.

06:55.000 --> 06:56.520
That's what the price is.

06:56.520 --> 07:02.440
But if you look at this, it does solve the problem of key distribution, but it makes this

07:02.440 --> 07:05.360
type of cryptography really slow.

07:05.360 --> 07:12.800
So if you remember the advantages of symmetric, very fast, but it has the problem of key distribution.

07:12.800 --> 07:15.560
This is the actual opposite, isn't it?

07:15.560 --> 07:20.160
Solves the problem of key distribution, but becomes very slow.

07:20.160 --> 07:23.640
And that's why the two are really complementary to each other.

07:23.640 --> 07:28.760
And we'll talk about that later on, but most cryptography solutions today end up being

07:28.760 --> 07:35.800
a combination of symmetric and asymmetric for what they're each good at.

07:35.800 --> 07:43.360
Symmetric is typically used for bulk and speed and asymmetric is used to exchange the symmetric

07:43.360 --> 07:48.600
keys that are required in both ends in order to be able to do things quickly.

07:48.600 --> 07:55.880
So today we have hybrid products, crypto systems that really combine symmetric algorithms

07:55.880 --> 08:01.720
and asymmetric together to be able to use them both for what they're really good at.

08:01.720 --> 08:07.600
So in summary, when you look at the advantages and disadvantages of asymmetric, it's going

08:07.600 --> 08:11.160
to be the opposite of what we had for symmetric.

08:11.160 --> 08:18.360
The advantage is that it solves the problem of key distribution, but it becomes really

08:18.360 --> 08:19.360
slow.

08:19.360 --> 08:24.560
Now one of the other problems that we had with symmetric was the scalability problem.

08:24.560 --> 08:30.080
If you add a whole bunch of people that need it to communicate securely with each other

08:30.080 --> 08:36.520
using symmetric key cryptography, the number of keys required was going to grow exponentially.

08:36.520 --> 08:43.680
In fact, I think we used an example of 1,000 people needing to communicate securely with

08:43.680 --> 08:47.600
each other, would require almost half a million keys.

08:47.600 --> 08:54.440
Well, this type of cryptography also solves the problem of scalability, because if we have

08:54.440 --> 09:00.520
1,000 people that need to communicate securely with each other, all that's required is a total

09:00.520 --> 09:07.240
of 2,000 keys, because every person has their key pair, private and public key.

09:07.240 --> 09:14.200
So 1,000 people total of 2,000 keys, that's a whole lot easier to manage than obviously

09:14.200 --> 09:16.960
almost half a million keys.

09:16.960 --> 09:22.200
So there are advantages and disadvantages to this, but that's why it makes sense to use

09:22.200 --> 09:25.440
them together, symmetric and asymmetric.

09:25.440 --> 09:28.680
So here's a slide that talks about how this works.

09:28.680 --> 09:34.000
And what you need to focus on here is that you start seeing how this type of cryptography

09:34.000 --> 09:40.320
actually provides some added advantages that we didn't have before with symmetric.

09:40.320 --> 09:47.200
But if you want to address confidentiality, what needs to happen here is the person sending

09:47.200 --> 09:53.320
me, for example, a secret message, will have to encrypt that message with my public key.

09:53.320 --> 09:58.680
To address confidentiality, you will always encrypt with the receiver's public key.

09:58.680 --> 10:04.720
All right, so it's the public key of the receiver that allows us to achieve confidentiality,

10:04.720 --> 10:10.880
because then the receiver will have to use their private key, which nobody else has.

10:10.880 --> 10:15.200
And so that ensures confidentiality of the message.

10:15.200 --> 10:18.840
You will always encrypt with the receiver's public key.

10:18.840 --> 10:22.400
Now here's something else though that we can achieve.

10:22.400 --> 10:29.880
So if you remember, let's say that I am going to encrypt a message with my private key,

10:29.880 --> 10:32.080
my private key.

10:32.080 --> 10:33.480
Who can read that message?

10:33.480 --> 10:38.620
Well, it's going to be anybody that has my public key, which I have to assume is the

10:38.620 --> 10:40.080
entire world.

10:40.080 --> 10:41.640
So why would I ever do that?

10:41.640 --> 10:46.880
Why would I ever encrypt a message with my private key, knowing that anyone out there

10:46.880 --> 10:51.000
that has my public key will be able to read that message?

10:51.000 --> 10:54.600
Because that obviously does not address confidentiality.

10:54.600 --> 10:56.400
Well here's the answer to that.

10:56.400 --> 11:01.160
If I encrypt a message with my private key and all of you can decrypt it with what you

11:01.160 --> 11:05.600
know is my public key, that proves to you where it came from.

11:05.600 --> 11:09.680
And so we're starting to address possibly something that's very important to address

11:09.680 --> 11:10.760
in today's environment.

